      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'Critics have long asked whether Kant\'s ethics is too rigid for the messy realities of human life. The infamous case of the inquiring murderer — must you tell the truth to a killer who asks where your friend is hiding? — has haunted Kantian ethics since Benjamin Constant first raised it. Kant himself seemed to bite the bullet, arguing that lying is always wrong even in such extreme cases, a stance that strikes many as morally monstrous. Yet defenders argue that the Categorical Imperative is more flexible than caricatures suggest, and that careful formulation of one\'s maxims can accommodate moral common sense. The ongoing struggle to apply Kantian principles to real dilemmas is itself a testament to the theory\'s depth and continuing vitality.' },
      { type: 'paragraph', text: 'What makes the Categorical Imperative enduringly powerful is not that it resolves every moral question but that it frames morality as something objective, rational, and universally binding. In an age of moral relativism and ethical exhaustion, Kant\'s insistence that there are principles we must follow regardless of our feelings offers a bracing challenge. His framework undergirds contemporary debates in bioethics, artificial intelligence ethics, and international law, wherever we seek principles that transcend cultural borders. The Categorical Imperative asks each of us a deceptively simple question: could you live in the world that your choices would create? It is a question that, once heard, becomes impossible to ignore.' }
