    bio: 'Hannah Arendt was born in Linden, Germany, to a secular Jewish family and grew up in Königsberg — the same city where Immanuel Kant had spent his entire life. She studied philosophy under Martin Heidegger and Karl Jaspers, earning her doctorate from the University of Heidelberg in 1929 with a dissertation on the concept of love in Saint Augustine. The rise of Nazism forced her to flee Germany in 1933; she lived as a stateless refugee in France before emigrating to the United States in 1941, where she eventually became a naturalized citizen and one of the most prominent public intellectuals of the twentieth century.\n\nArendt\'s major works — The Origins of Totalitarianism (1951), The Human Condition (1958), and Eichmann in Jerusalem (1963) — explored the nature of political evil, the conditions of human freedom, and the relationship between thought and moral responsibility. Her concept of the "banality of evil," coined during her coverage of Adolf Eichmann\'s trial in Jerusalem, argued that the most horrifying atrocities can be committed by ordinary people who fail to think critically about what they are doing. This insight deeply challenged conventional assumptions about evil as the product of monstrous individuals and redirected attention to the systemic, bureaucratic, and cognitive conditions that enable mass violence.\n\nThroughout her career, Arendt insisted on the importance of active citizenship, public deliberation, and the capacity for independent judgment. She drew on Greek, Roman, and modern philosophical traditions to argue that political life — the space where humans appear before one another as equals and act in concert — is the highest expression of human freedom. Her work continues to shape debates on democracy, human rights, refugee crises, and the ethics of political participation, making her one of the most relevant philosophers for our contemporary moment.',
